From e32e489f89ca1d538c171ec2cda46b66354f9d1d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 14:37:07 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] um/x86: build with -fcf-protection=none

Native x86 kernel builds pass -fcf-protection=none explicitly unless
CONFIG_X86_KERNEL_IBT re-enables branch protection. The UML makefiles
never set the flag, so toolchains that default to -fcf-protection=full
(e.g. Ubuntu and Fedora host compilers) prepend a 4-byte endbr64 to
every kernel function.

UML cannot use CET, so the endbr64 markers are dead weight, and they
break BPF trampoline attachment: the patchable_function_entry(5, 0)
NOP slot of the synthetic __x64_sys_* wrappers is displaced from
function entry, so BPF text-poke byte comparison finds endbr64 where
it expects NOPs and attaching fentry/fexit programs fails with -EBUSY
on hosts whose compiler enables CET by default.

Pass -fcf-protection=none for UML builds, matching native x86.

Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
---
 arch/x86/Makefile.um | 6 ++++++
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+)

diff --git a/arch/x86/Makefile.um b/arch/x86/Makefile.um
index f65289362..9a574ffd8 100644
--- a/arch/x86/Makefile.um
+++ b/arch/x86/Makefile.um
@@ -2,6 +2,12 @@
 core-y += arch/x86/crypto/
 core-y += arch/x86/net/
 
+# Match arch/x86: CET is not supported on UML. Compilers that default to
+# -fcf-protection=full prepend endbr64 to every function, which displaces
+# the patchable_function_entry() slot that BPF text poking expects at
+# function entry.
+KBUILD_CFLAGS += $(call cc-option,-fcf-protection=none)
+
 #
 # Disable SSE and other FP/SIMD instructions to match normal x86
 # This is required to work around issues in older LLVM versions, but breaks
-- 
2.43.0

